[[File:Chlororespiration basics.jpg|thumb|Chlororespiration basics]] '''Chlororespiration''' is a process in [[plant]] [[chloroplast]]s which is thought to involve a respiratory electron transport chain within the [[thylakoid]] membrane.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Sonia |last1=Cruz|first2=Reimund |last2=Goss|first3=Christian |last3=Wilhelm|first4= Richard|last4= Leegood|first5= Peter |last5=Horton|first6=Torsten |last6=Jakob3|title=Impact of chlororespiration on non-photochemical quenching of chlorophyll fluorescence and on the regulation of the diadinoxanthin cycle in the diatom Thalassiosira pseudonana|journal=Journal of Experimental Botany|volume=62|issue=2|pages=509–519|date=January 2011|doi=10.1093/jxb/erq284}}</ref> It is thought to involve a proton pumping respiratory [[dehydrogenase]] (the Ndh complex), and Immutans, an oxidase similar to the [[mitochondria]]l [[alternative oxidase]], which reduces the [[plastoquinone]] pool.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Nixon | first1 = P. J. | title = Chlororespiration | doi = 10.1098/rstb.2000.0714 | journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences | volume = 355 | issue = 1402 | pages = 1541–1547| year = 2000 | pmid = | pmc = 1692878}}</ref> This process may function to balance [[adenosine triphosphate|ATP]]''':''' reductant levels in the chloroplast at night, when cyclic electron transfer around [[Photosystem I]] cannot occur.
