{{short description|1966 film by Andy Warhol}} {{Infobox film | name = Eating Too Fast | image = | alt = <!-- see WP:ALT --> | caption = | director = [[Andy Warhol]] | producer = Andy Warhol | writer = | screenplay = | story = | starring = Gregory Battcock | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = | distributor = | released = 1966 <!-- {{Film date|Year|Month|Day|Location}} --> | runtime = 67 minutes | country = United States | language = English | budget = | gross = }} '''''Eating Too Fast''''' is a 1966 [[Andy Warhol]] film made at [[The Factory]]. It was originally titled '''''Blow Job #2''''' and features art critic and writer Gregory Battcock (1937–1980). The film is 67 minutes long and is, in effect, a black and white [[sound film]] remake of Warhol's ''[[Blow Job (film)|Blow Job]]'' (1964). Battcock had previously appeared in Warhol's films ''[[Batman Dracula]]'' (1964) and ''Horse'' (1965).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.warholstars.org/warhol/warhol1/warhol1f/eating.html |title=WarholStars entry |access-date=2012-01-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219215924/http://www.warholstars.org/warhol/warhol1/warhol1f/eating.html |archive-date=2011-12-19 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
==Production background== The [[British Film Institute]] catalogue says that the first half of the film is a still shot, showing Battcock eating an apple and taking a phone call, while apparently receiving [[fellatio]]. The second half of the film has more camera movement. Battcock's diaries say the film was made in Battcock's [[Greenwich Village]] apartment with Warhol and [[Lou Reed]] present for the filming.
