'''Paragone''' ({{lang-it|paragone}}, meaning ''comparison''), was a debate from the [[Italian Renaissance]] in which painting and sculpture (and to a degree architecture) were each championed as superior to - and therefore distinct from - the others.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/804911527|title=Baroque and Rococo|last=A.|first=Bailey, Gauvin|publisher=|year=|isbn=9780714857428|location=London|pages=9|oclc=804911527}}</ref>
[[Leonardo da Vinci]]'s [[A Treatise on Painting|treatise on painting]], noting the difficulty of painting and supremacy of sight, is a noted example. [[Giorgio Vasari]] argues that drawing is the father of all arts, and as such, the most important one.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Vasari|first1=Giorgio|title=Lives of the Most Excellent Painters, Sculptors, and Architects|date=1550}}</ref>
